Develop an anomaly detection solution.

## Task
Train an anomaly detection model on ./data/train/ (normal images), then score 
every image in ./data/test_images/ for how anomalous it is. This is a one-class 
setting: train data is all normal, test data is a mix of normal and anomalous.

## Required outputs (exact format)
Create ./outputs/ containing:
1. ./outputs/image_scores.json — JSON object mapping each test filename to a 
   single float anomaly score (higher = more anomalous). Include EVERY test file.
2. ./outputs/pixel_scores/ — one PNG per test image, same filename, 
   single-channel, 256x256.
3. ./outputs/train.py and ./outputs/infer.py
4. ./outputs/requirements.txt
5. ./outputs/README.md (how to run)

## Method specification
- Use a feature-based anomaly detection approach: extract features from test 
  images using an ImageNet-pretrained CNN backbone, and detect anomalies by 
  comparing test features against the distribution of normal training features. 
  (Do not use reconstruction-based or generative approaches.)
- Preprocessing: resize all input images to 256x256 before feature extraction.
- Pixel anomaly map: produce a per-pixel anomaly score, then resize to 256x256.
- Image-level score: aggregate the pixel anomaly map into a single image score.

## Implementation specification
- Feature extraction: use mid-level layers of the backbone (not the final 
  classification layer); concatenate features from at least two depth levels.
- Pixel map post-processing: apply Gaussian smoothing to the anomaly map before 
  resizing.
- Score normalization: normalize image-level scores to a consistent range.
- Code structure: separate the pipeline into distinct functions for 
  (a) feature extraction, (b) normal-feature modeling/storage, (c) scoring. 
  Keep configuration values (paths, image size, layer choices) in a separate 
  config section or file, not hardcoded inline.

## Constraints (apply to all)
- Use ONLY ./data/train/ for training and ./data/test_images/ for scoring.
- Do NOT read, open, search, or reference anything under ./ground_truth/.
  Do not look for labels or masks anywhere.
- Do NOT ask questions mid-task. Work autonomously: write code, install packages,
  train, run inference, fix errors, re-run until outputs exist.

When finished, print what method and backbone you chose.

